  "prompt": "Is Prime Minister of India a constitutional post?",
  "response": "Yes, the position of the Prime Minister of India is considered a constitutional post, even though the title \"Prime Minister\" is not explicitly mentioned in the Constitution of India. The role and functions of the Prime Minister are derived from various provisions within the Constitution and judicial interpretations.\n\n### Constitutional Basis\n\n1. **Appointment and Role:**\n   - **Article 75:** This article states that the Prime Minister shall be appointed by the President, and the other Ministers shall be appointed on the advice of the Prime Minister. It outlines that the Council of Ministers shall aid and advise the President on the exercise of his functions.\n   - **Article 74:** Establishes that there shall be a Council of Ministers with the Prime Minister at its head to aid and advise the President.\n\n2. **Leadership of the Government:**\n   - The Prime Minister acts as the principal executive authority in the country, leading the Union Council of Ministers and playing a central role in policy-making and administration.\n\n### Judicial Interpretation\n\nThe Supreme Court of India has affirmed that the position of the Prime Minister is indeed constitutional. In various judgments, the Court has interpreted the collective responsibility and the role of the Prime Minister based on the constitutional framework, thereby recognizing it as a position established by the Constitution.\n\n### Summary\n\nWhile the Constitution does not explicitly use the term \"Prime Minister,\" the role is intrinsically linked to the constitutional provisions governing the executive branch of the government. The responsibilities, powers, and the very existence of the Prime Minister are derived from the Constitution, making it a constitutional post in the Indian political system.",
